Janus is a bidirectional Windows driver-translation framework with a security and digital-preservation mission: keep the world's stranded legacy systems both alive and migratable. A large, quietly critical population of industrial, medical, utility, and laboratory equipment is frozen on Windows 9x (and embedded XP, NT4, and older) because a vital device driver was never ported forward. Janus translates those drivers in both directions. Forward, it backports Windows NT4 ScsiPort and NT5 (2000/XP) WDM kernel drivers to Windows 9x, keeping vintage systems repairable. Reverse, it runs Win9x VxDs as NT/ReactOS kernel drivers, so an unpatchable host can be retired onto a modern maintained kernel while its irreplaceable hardware keeps working. The same loader is equally a tool for digital preservation and software archaeology: retro gaming and emulation, computing museums keeping exhibits runnable, digital forensics booting and instrumenting seized legacy systems, and the study of vanished software, all of which need unmodified vintage drivers executing in an instrumented, sandboxed environment. The toolkit corrects LE binary headers, deploys to FAT32 disk images, provides a WDM compatibility layer, and includes diagnostic tools for VxD/PE analysis. Origin: a NEC ATAPI miniport on Windows 98 SE.
